  Adaon says, "As a bard ye would ha' a wide range o' >talents< at 
your disposal.  If there's one thing a bard is, it's versatile.  Jack of all 
trades, y'know.
  "One o' the first things ye learn as a bard are a few feats of manual 
dexterity.  Sleight o' hand, ye could call it."  Adaon smiles.  "Aye, 
sleight of hand.  Ye also get a bit of schoolin' o' old tales and legends.  
They are nae only a good story t' tell to folks, but are also a might 
useful on y'r travels.  The guild will supply ye wi' a >lute<, which aids 
in the use o' y'r >talents<.
  "We teach ye a bit of ventriloquism then, and how t' earn y'rsel' a 
bit o' money if y' nae be in shape to fight for it.  After that, ye will 
learn a wide variety of musical styles with a range of applications in 
adventuring life.  It be nigh impossible t' list all the things ye can do 
with >music<, and we >bards< are always coming up wi' more.  We 
throw in a bit o' acting, and mime, so ye can be more impressive and 
expressive without saying a word.
  "O' course," Adaon chuckles, "we bards're no stranger to strong drink.
Ye'll be able to drink anyone else under the table, all the while
maintainin' a clear head yerself... well, more or less.  Now that's
what I call talent, eh?
  "Ye can eventualy will learn some chants that inspire and otherwise
aid in combat."
  Adaon leans upon the desk, awaiting another question.
